00:15:31,598 --> 00:15:34,101
My baby just cares for me!

253
00:15:34,434 --> 00:15:36,645
His baby just cares for...

254
00:15:37,271 --> 00:15:39,690
My baby just cares for me!

255
00:15:45,821 --> 00:15:47,614
Mrs Holden Spence.

256
00:15:47,823 --> 00:15:49,491
Skylar Spence. I love it.

257
00:15:49,741 --> 00:15:52,035
He’s taking her
to Le Cirque tonight.

258
00:15:52,244 --> 00:15:54,621
-No kidding?
-I think he’s going to propose.

259
00:15:54,872 --> 00:15:56,999
And I introduced them.

260
00:15:57,166 --> 00:15:58,792
We’ve heard it, Dad.

261
00:15:59,042 --> 00:16:01,587
I did. He came to work
at our law firm.

262
00:16:01,795 --> 00:16:03,172
The first day I said:

263
00:16:03,380 --> 00:16:07,050
‘This kid’s great. His feet are on
the ground. He’s perfect for her.’

264
00:16:07,259 --> 00:16:09,011
Frieda, the pasta
has no sauce.

265
00:16:09,261 --> 00:16:11,471
Bavarian pasta
doesn’t need sauce.

266
00:16:11,680 --> 00:16:14,474
Italian pasta needs sauce.
The italians were weak.

267
00:16:14,683 --> 00:16:16,351
Fine. Give me some pepper.

268
00:16:16,518 --> 00:16:21,231
Your solution to rampant crime
is just to let criminals go free?

269
00:16:21,398 --> 00:16:24,067
No. Charles Ferry
deserves a parole.

270
00:16:24,276 --> 00:16:27,696
You want someone like
this out on the streets?

271
00:16:27,905 --> 00:16:31,325
Armed robbery, assault,
attempted escape.

272
00:16:31,533 --> 00:16:33,994
-He was an abused child.
-Have some compassion.

273
00:16:34,203 --> 00:16:37,498
He went to prison for life because
of his horrible childhood.

274
00:16:37,706 --> 00:16:39,625
Something you know nothing about.

275
00:16:39,833 --> 00:16:41,627
-Then one mistake...
-Are you kidding?

276
00:16:41,835 --> 00:16:43,337
A bad trial,
corrupt judges...

277
00:16:43,587 --> 00:16:45,297
Calm down, both of you.

278
00:16:45,506 --> 00:16:48,842
-I don’t want to discuss this.
-I can’t listen to this.

279
00:16:49,092 --> 00:16:50,802
-I need my wallet.
-Where’re you going?

280
00:16:51,011 --> 00:16:53,722
The Polo Grounds.
Giants and Cardinals are playing.

281
00:16:53,931 --> 00:16:57,809
You can’t go out. If you want to
take a walk, go with Frieda.

282
00:16:58,060 --> 00:17:00,395
But they’re playing
today, Labour Day.

283
00:17:00,646 --> 00:17:01,772
It’s June, Grandpa.

284
00:17:02,022 --> 00:17:04,691
The Polo Grounds
closed years ago.

285
00:17:04,900 --> 00:17:07,361
-Rained out?
-Take him for a short walk.

286
00:17:07,611 --> 00:17:09,363
No, I’m not going with Frieda.

287
00:17:09,613 --> 00:17:13,075
No, no, not with her. I don’t
need a German Shepherd.

288
00:17:13,283 --> 00:17:14,618
Take a nice walk.

289
00:17:14,868 --> 00:17:16,495
You know what the kids say?

290
00:17:17,371 --> 00:17:20,499
They think Holden’s giving a
surprise to Skylar tonight.

291
00:17:20,666 --> 00:17:23,710
If you keep gossiping about
it, it won’t be a surprise.

292
00:17:23,919 --> 00:17:25,254
I told you not to tell.

293
00:17:25,462 --> 00:17:29,424
I’m going out. If Minnie calls,
tell her I’m at the Polo Grounds.

294
00:17:29,675 --> 00:17:31,677
Minnie’s been dead 20 years.

295
00:17:31,927 --> 00:17:35,347
I’m not arguing that. But if
she calls, i’ll be home later.

296
00:17:36,098 --> 00:17:38,100
21 is too young to get married.

297
00:17:38,350 --> 00:17:41,186
If this was anyone but
Holden, i’d be against it.

298
00:17:41,395 --> 00:17:43,814
No way I’m getting
married till I’m 35.

299
00:17:44,064 --> 00:17:46,233
Then I’ll probably
live with a woman.

300
00:17:46,483 --> 00:17:47,734
Why do you make these jokes?

301
00:17:48,026 --> 00:17:49,361
You like Holden, right?

302
00:17:49,611 --> 00:17:53,282
The problem is Skylar.
She’s a romantic twit.

303
00:17:53,615 --> 00:17:55,617
Holden’s not romantic
enough for her.

304
00:17:55,826 --> 00:17:58,287
So what? She’s going
to marry him, right?

305
00:17:58,495 --> 00:18:00,831
I hope so. I want her
room when she does.

306
00:18:01,039 --> 00:18:02,833
She should leap at this guy.

307
00:18:03,041 --> 00:18:05,669
Skylar suffers from
white knight syndrome.

308
00:18:05,919 --> 00:18:09,089
Since her hormones kicked in,
she’s hoped for some...

309
00:18:09,298 --> 00:18:11,425
charismatic guy to
sweep her off her feet.

310
00:18:11,675 --> 00:18:14,887
So Holden is that young
Lochinvar, all right?

311
00:18:15,137 --> 00:18:16,263
He’s a young schnook.

312
00:18:16,471 --> 00:18:19,266
He’s a schnook, but
he’s a loveable schnook.

313
00:18:19,516 --> 00:18:22,436
What an endorsement! I’m
never bringing a guy home.

314
00:18:23,478 --> 00:18:25,856
In the first place,
he’s not a schnook.

315
00:18:39,870 --> 00:18:41,705
I’m a dreamer...

316
00:18:43,999 --> 00:18:45,876
aren’t we all?

317
00:18:48,378 --> 00:18:50,255
Just a dreamer...

318
00:18:52,216 --> 00:18:54,009
aren’t we all?

319
00:18:56,178 --> 00:18:59,223
In my dreams, each
night it seems...

320
00:19:03,894 --> 00:19:06,271
my sweetheart comes to call.

321
00:19:13,654 --> 00:19:16,114
He’s so charming,
strong and tall.

322
00:19:21,870 --> 00:19:24,331
It’s alarming
howl fall.

323
00:19:29,127 --> 00:19:31,004
He’s ideal.

324
00:19:32,798 --> 00:19:35,342
But then he isn’t
real and I’m a fool.

325
00:19:41,306 --> 00:19:43,183
But aren’t we all?

326
00:19:54,528 --> 00:19:56,655
Can I tell you
how I see us?

327
00:19:56,905 --> 00:19:57,656
How?

328
00:19:57,990 --> 00:20:01,493
We get married and we live
by my parents in Sharon.

329
00:20:01,702 --> 00:20:03,704
I could never
leave New York.

330
00:20:04,121 --> 00:20:07,249
We leave my parents in Sharon,
right? We live in New York.

331
00:20:07,499 --> 00:20:10,919
It’s just that we may want
more space if we have 4 kids.

332
00:20:11,170 --> 00:20:12,588
I want two children.

333
00:20:13,839 --> 00:20:15,215
Two is perfect.

334
00:20:15,465 --> 00:20:17,176
Two is perfect for me...

335
00:20:17,426 --> 00:20:18,886
because four is...

336
00:20:19,094 --> 00:20:20,345
really a lot and...

337
00:20:20,846 --> 00:20:22,514
you’ll stay at home...

338
00:20:22,764 --> 00:20:24,141
No, I’ll be working.

339
00:20:24,600 --> 00:20:28,687
When not working full-time.
You’ll have a career. Journalism.

340
00:20:29,021 --> 00:20:30,355
Architecture.

341
00:20:31,899 --> 00:20:33,567
Architecture? Since when?

342
00:20:33,817 --> 00:20:36,361
I don’t know, just
some thoughts I’ve had.

343
00:20:36,612 --> 00:20:39,072
I mean, you majored
in journalism, but...

344
00:20:39,781 --> 00:20:41,825
The important thing is...

345
00:20:42,117 --> 00:20:45,287
that we agree on just about
everything, it seems.

346
00:20:45,496 --> 00:20:47,456
Shall I bring the dessert, sir?

347
00:20:47,998 --> 00:20:51,043
It’s time for
dessert? Yes, it is.

348
00:20:51,251 --> 00:20:54,087
Excuse me a second. I’ll
just tend to a small matter.

349
00:20:54,963 --> 00:20:57,132
It’s ready, just as you wished.

350
00:20:57,382 --> 00:20:58,550
Think it’ll work?

351
00:20:59,510 --> 00:21:01,053
That’s perfect, Umberto.

352
00:21:01,261 --> 00:21:02,262
Glad you like it, sir.

353
00:21:02,471 --> 00:21:04,765
Let me show you
my end of the deal.

354
00:21:05,390 --> 00:21:06,600
That’s a honey, huh?

355
00:21:06,808 --> 00:21:09,269
Set me back a bit,
I don’t mind saying.

356
00:21:09,478 --> 00:21:12,689
I’m sure. A brilliant
idea. Very romantic.

357
00:21:13,398 --> 00:21:14,900
That’s the kind of guy I am.

358
00:21:15,150 --> 00:21:16,235
I can see that.

359
00:21:16,485 --> 00:21:19,154
Here we go. I’m just going
to lay that right there.

360
00:21:19,404 --> 00:21:21,740
Will that knock her socks off?

361
00:21:21,949 --> 00:21:22,491
Shall we?

362
00:21:22,699 --> 00:21:24,493
Go ahead. I’m relying on you.

363
00:21:24,701 --> 00:21:25,619
Good luck.

364
00:21:28,247 --> 00:21:29,623
Everything okay?

365
00:21:29,873 --> 00:21:30,707
No problem.

366
00:21:30,874 --> 00:21:32,543
-Shall we order dessert?
-I did.

367
00:21:32,709 --> 00:21:33,293
You did?

368
00:21:33,544 --> 00:21:36,630
You like take-charge guys, and
I’m coming through for you.

369
00:21:36,880 --> 00:21:38,423
It’s not like you.

370
00:21:38,632 --> 00:21:42,344
Anything for you. Umberto,
will you do the honours?

371
00:21:43,220 --> 00:21:44,930
My God, it’s delicious!

372
00:21:45,138 --> 00:21:47,307
Peach, my
favourite flavour.

373
00:21:48,433 --> 00:21:51,228
-It’s delicious.
-What are you doing? Stop!

374
00:21:51,478 --> 00:21:53,146
-Where’s the rest of it?
-What?

375
00:21:53,355 --> 00:21:55,107
The cream and the cherry!

376
00:21:55,315 --> 00:21:57,192
-I ate them.
-You ate the ring?

377
00:21:57,359 --> 00:21:57,943
What?

378
00:21:58,193 --> 00:22:00,195
-I bought you a diamond ring.
-You did?

379
00:22:00,445 --> 00:22:01,530
At Harry Winston’s.

380
00:22:01,738 --> 00:22:02,739
Where is it?

381
00:22:02,948 --> 00:22:04,032
It was on the dessert.

382
00:22:04,283 --> 00:22:04,950
Why?

383
00:22:05,117 --> 00:22:08,704
-I thought it’d be romantic!
-To put a ring on ice cream?

384
00:22:09,288 --> 00:22:11,832
It wasn’t my idea,
it was DJ’s.

385
00:22:11,999 --> 00:22:14,793
She said it would give
it dramatic flair.

386
00:22:15,085 --> 00:22:16,295
I ate a diamond ring?

387
00:22:16,503 --> 00:22:20,007
I turn round for 2 seconds and
$8,000 goes down your throat.

388
00:22:20,299 --> 00:22:21,925
Oh, my God!

389
00:22:22,134 --> 00:22:23,135
Stay calm.

390
00:22:23,343 --> 00:22:24,511
How big was it?

391
00:22:24,761 --> 00:22:25,929
It was a big rock.

392
00:22:26,180 --> 00:22:29,016
-I swallowed what, a carat?
-A karat-and-a-half.

393
00:22:29,266 --> 00:22:30,225
You’d like two carrots?

394
00:22:30,434 --> 00:22:31,351
I’m dying!

395
00:22:31,560 --> 00:22:32,186
You’re not.

396
00:22:32,394 --> 00:22:33,270
Something wrong, sir?

397
00:22:33,478 --> 00:22:36,356
Just swallowed a little
jewelry, it’s all right.

398
00:22:36,565 --> 00:22:37,649
-How could you?
-Enjoy your dinner.

399
00:22:37,900 --> 00:22:42,196
How could l? Most people look at
their food before plunging into it.

400
00:22:42,404 --> 00:22:43,864
Let me check your mouth.

401
00:22:45,699 --> 00:22:47,618
This isn’t much of a problem.

402
00:22:47,743 --> 00:22:50,204
It’s in an accessible place.

403
00:22:50,412 --> 00:22:52,664
It’s an absolutely
beautiful ring.

404
00:22:52,873 --> 00:22:54,666
A brilliant choice.

405
00:22:54,917 --> 00:22:56,793
Congratulations, girl.

406
00:22:57,085 --> 00:22:58,754
It is beautiful.

407
00:22:59,296 --> 00:23:01,048
Look, she got engaged.

408
00:23:01,298 --> 00:23:03,175
What is it, two karats?

409
00:23:03,383 --> 00:23:04,009
One-and-a-half.

410
00:23:04,259 --> 00:23:05,135
White gold?

411
00:23:05,385 --> 00:23:06,303
Solid platinum.

412
00:23:06,470 --> 00:23:07,387
That’s good.

413
00:23:07,638 --> 00:23:08,889
-Harry Winston’s.
-How much?

414
00:23:09,139 --> 00:23:10,224
8,000.

415
00:23:10,516 --> 00:23:13,810
I can get the same ring for you
for 6 from my brother-in-law.

416
00:23:14,061 --> 00:23:15,604
You’re paying for the name.

417
00:23:15,771 --> 00:23:17,689
He’s a wonderful man.

418
00:23:18,482 --> 00:23:19,858
Am I going to scar?

419
00:23:20,150 --> 00:23:23,529
Doctors look at X-rays
but they seldom grin.

420
00:23:24,279 --> 00:23:26,490
I’m always on the
outside...

421
00:23:26,698 --> 00:23:28,200
looking in.

422
00:23:28,450 --> 00:23:31,119
Maybe that’s why
I see the funny side...

423
00:23:32,454 --> 00:23:35,415
When I see a fallen
brother take a bride.

424
00:23:36,834 --> 00:23:39,294
Weddings make a
lot of people sad.

425
00:23:40,879 --> 00:23:42,840
But if you're not the groom...

426
00:23:43,590 --> 00:23:45,509
you’re not so bad.

427
00:23:47,970 --> 00:23:50,806
Another bride,
anothergroom...

428
00:23:51,849 --> 00:23:53,809
another sunny honeymoon.

429
00:23:55,769 --> 00:23:57,479
Another season...

430
00:23:57,729 --> 00:23:59,273
another reason...

431
00:23:59,606 --> 00:24:01,567
for making whoopee.

432
00:24:03,610 --> 00:24:05,445
A lot of shoes...

433
00:24:05,779 --> 00:24:07,406
a lot of rice...

434
00:24:07,656 --> 00:24:09,158
the groom is nervous...

435
00:24:09,575 --> 00:24:11,326
he answers twice.

436
00:24:11,577 --> 00:24:13,203
It’s really killing...

437
00:24:13,370 --> 00:24:14,913
that’s he’s so willing...

438
00:24:15,289 --> 00:24:17,207
to make whoopee.

439
00:24:19,918 --> 00:24:22,129
Picture a little
love nest...

440
00:24:23,755 --> 00:24:26,300
down where the roses cling...

441
00:24:27,634 --> 00:24:30,137
picture the same
sweet love nest...

442
00:24:31,471 --> 00:24:33,891
think what a year can bring.

443
00:24:34,933 --> 00:24:36,643
He’s washing dishes...

444
00:24:36,852 --> 00:24:38,228
and baby clothes...

445
00:24:38,729 --> 00:24:40,439
he’s so ambitious...

446
00:24:40,814 --> 00:24:42,649
he even sews.

447
00:24:42,900 --> 00:24:44,693
But don’t forget folks...

448
00:24:45,027 --> 00:24:46,737
that’s what you get, folks...

449
00:24:46,945 --> 00:24:48,405
for making whoopee.

450
00:24:48,572 --> 00:24:50,491
Just for making whoopee.

451
00:25:34,243 --> 00:25:35,953
He’s washing dishes...

452
00:25:36,161 --> 00:25:37,830
and baby clothes...

453
00:25:38,205 --> 00:25:39,957
he’s so ambitious...

454
00:25:40,165 --> 00:25:41,875
he even sews.

455
00:25:42,084 --> 00:25:43,794
But don’t forget folks...

456
00:25:45,754 --> 00:25:48,173
that’s what you get, folks...

457
00:26:03,814 --> 00:26:07,568
Summer came, and Lane and
Laura got jobs at the Met...

458
00:26:08,068 --> 00:26:09,820
and spent weekends
at the beach.

459
00:26:10,529 --> 00:26:14,449
Mom organised a petition for
Charles Ferry’s parole.

460
00:26:15,075 --> 00:26:16,410
Her new pet cause.

461
00:26:16,660 --> 00:26:20,205
She even visited the prison and
was appalled by the conditions.

462
00:26:20,664 --> 00:26:23,125
What we need are open prisons.

463
00:26:23,375 --> 00:26:27,171
Space where the damaged
human spirit can heal.

464
00:26:28,046 --> 00:26:32,426
Give them an opportunity to
decorate their own cells...

465
00:26:32,759 --> 00:26:35,220
with their own
personal decorators.

466
00:26:36,096 --> 00:26:37,306
And better cuisine.

467
00:26:37,598 --> 00:26:39,099
European menus.

468
00:26:39,474 --> 00:26:43,187
As for me, over the years I was
used to splitting summers up...

469
00:26:43,478 --> 00:26:46,607
July with Mom in New York,
and August with Dad in Europe.

470
00:26:46,815 --> 00:26:49,985
Usually it was Paris, but this
time he took me to Venice.

471
00:26:50,360 --> 00:26:53,906
I think he wanted to get over
memories of losing Giselle.

472
00:26:54,114 --> 00:26:57,659
All I can say is if we’re
talking about romantic cities...

473
00:26:57,910 --> 00:27:00,496
they’ve got the most
gorgeous guys there...

474
00:27:00,704 --> 00:27:03,624
and they can’t keep their
hands off you. It’s great.

475
00:27:03,832 --> 00:27:07,711
The first week was just heaven
for me. Having a ball...

476
00:27:07,961 --> 00:27:09,546
sailing on gondolas.

477
00:27:09,796 --> 00:27:12,382
But Dad just seemed to
hang around the hotel.

478
00:27:13,091 --> 00:27:15,219
Giselle was still
haunting him.

479
00:27:15,552 --> 00:27:17,429
I’m through with love.

480
00:27:18,514 --> 00:27:20,933
I’ll never fall again.

481
00:27:21,767 --> 00:27:24,269
Said ‘adieu’ to love.

482
00:27:25,270 --> 00:27:27,856
Don’t ever call again.

483
00:27:28,482 --> 00:27:30,943
For I must have you or no-one.

484
00:27:36,448 --> 00:27:38,951
And so I’m through with love.

485
00:27:42,955 --> 00:27:44,790
I’ve locked my heart...

486
00:27:45,999 --> 00:27:48,210
I’ll keep my
feelings there.

487
00:27:49,503 --> 00:27:52,172
I’ve stocked my heart...

488
00:27:53,215 --> 00:27:55,008
with icy frigid air.

489
00:27:56,635 --> 00:27:59,054
And I mean to
fall for no-one...

490
00:28:04,643 --> 00:28:06,645
because I’m through with love.

491
00:28:10,732 --> 00:28:12,734
I feel so guilty.

492
00:28:12,985 --> 00:28:14,862
-You should have fun.
-I am.

493
00:28:15,070 --> 00:28:17,781
I still can’t figure out what
went wrong with Giselle.

494
00:28:18,073 --> 00:28:20,576
I always thought she
was a little flighty.

495
00:28:20,784 --> 00:28:23,245
Want a drink?
I’ll have a beer.

496
00:28:23,453 --> 00:28:24,538
A Bellini.

497
00:28:25,956 --> 00:28:27,332
Let me give you this advice.

498
00:28:27,583 --> 00:28:31,378
When a relationship breaks
up, and I hope they don’t...

499
00:28:32,379 --> 00:28:36,300
Better to be the leaver than the
leavee, ‘cause the leaver leaves.

500
00:28:36,884 --> 00:28:38,302
But the leavee is left.

501
00:28:38,510 --> 00:28:39,428
It’s terrible.

502
00:28:39,678 --> 00:28:43,390
The worst that happens to the
leaver is a little survivor guilt.

503
00:28:43,599 --> 00:28:47,102
Survivor guilt is the worst thing
that should ever happen to you.

504
00:28:47,352 --> 00:28:49,396
Tomorrow i'll spend with you.

505
00:28:49,563 --> 00:28:51,648
It’s not necessary, really.

